ultiple test cases where each entry has a \"mutant_id\" and an \"is_fault_adjacent\" boolean indicating whether it is adjacent to another mutant causing a fault.\n\n### Approach\n1. **Understand the Input Data**: Each entry in the JSON represents a mutant ID and whether it is adjacent to another mutant that causes a fault.\n2. **Identify Adjacent Mutants**: For each mutant, check if there exists another mutant with an ID that is numerically consecutive (i.e., the next or previous number) within the same class name.\n3. **Determine Fault Status**: Based on the provided data, check if any adjacent mutant has the \"is_fault_adjacent\" set to true.\n\n### Solution Code\n```python\nimport json\n\n# Sample JSON input containing test cases\ndata = {\n    \"mutant_id\": \"src-main-java-org-joda-time-chrono-ZonedChronology-27-3\",\n    \"is_fault_adjacent\": True\n}\n\ndef find_adjacent_mutant(mutant_id, data):\n    # Split the mutant_id into parts to get the class and number components\n    parts = mutant_id.split('-')\n    class_name = '-'.join(parts[:-1])\n    current_number = int(parts[-1])\n\n    # Check each entry in the data for adjacent mutants\n    for entry in data:\n        if (entry[\"mutant_id\"].split('-')[-1] == str(current_number + 1) and \n            '-'.join(entry[\"mutant_id\"].split('-')[:-1]) == class_name):\n            return True\n\n    # Check for previous number adjacency\n    if current_number > 0:\n        for entry in data:\n            if (entry[\"mutant_id\"].split('-')[-1] == str(current_number - 1) and \n                '-'.join(entry[\"mutant_id\"].split('-')[:-1]) == class_name):\n                return True\n\n    # If no adjacent mutant found, return False\n    return False\n\n# Example usage\nadjacent_fault = find_adjacent_mutant(data[\"mutant_id\"], data)\nprint(adjacent_fault)\n```\n\n### Explanation\n- **Data Structure**: The input is a JSON object where each entry represents a mutant with its ID and fault status.\n- **Functionality*